<sn><md>### Interaction of Light with Matter

When light energy strikes a material, these main processes may occur:

![diagram](https://www.mrwaynesclass.com/lightOptics/pics/LightBehavior.png)

| **Process**      | **Description**                                                                             | **Key Points**                                                                                                                           |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Absorption**   | Material takes in specific wavelengths of light.                                            | • Electrons jump to higher energy levels after absorbing energy.<br>• Absorbed wavelengths match the energy gap between electron levels. |
| **Emission**     | Excited electrons fall back to lower energy levels and emit light.                          | • Produces bright spectral lines.<br>• Each element/compound emits unique wavelengths.                                                   |
| **Transmission** | Light passes through a material without being absorbed.                                     | • Seen in transparent or semi-transparent materials.<br>• Less interaction with electrons.                                               |
| **Reflection**   | Light bounces off the surface of a material.                                                | • Dominant in opaque materials.<br>• Angle of incidence equals angle of reflection.                                                      |
| **Diffraction**  | Bending or spreading of light when it passes around edges or through small openings.        | • Occurs when opening size ≈ wavelength of light.<br>• Creates interference patterns (bright and dark fringes).                          |
| **Scattering**   | Light is redirected in many directions due to interaction with particles or irregularities. | • Depends on particle size (Rayleigh, Mie scattering).<br>• Causes blue sky (Rayleigh) and white clouds (Mie).                           |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Types of Spectra{.text-center}

##### Continuous (Normal) Spectrum
A continuous band of colors or wavelengths `without gaps`.
Example: Sunlight or incandescent bulb light passed through a prism.

Produced by:

* Heated solids
* Dense gases
* Blackbody radiation

![diagram](https://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/word-image364.png)

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
##### Absorption Spectrum{.text-center}
A continuous spectrum with specific `dark lines or bands where light is absorbed`.

Produced when:

* Continuous light passes through a cooler gas or material
* The gas absorbs certain wavelengths

This gives “missing wavelengths” which help identify substances.

Example: Solar absorption lines (Fraunhofer lines).
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
##### Emission Spectrum{.text-center}
A `dark background with bright lines` at specific wavelengths.

Produced when:

* A material is excited (electrically or thermally)
* It emits light as electrons drop to lower energy levels

Each element has a unique emission spectrum.

Example: Sodium lamp gives two bright yellow lines (Na doublet).
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### How Spectroscopy Identifies Unknown Materials{.text-center}

Spectroscopy works like a fingerprint method.

##### Measure the Spectrum

Record the absorption or emission spectrum of the unknown material using a spectrometer.

#### Compare Peaks or Lines

Each compound shows characteristic wavelengths where:

* It absorbs
* It emits
* It reflects

For example:

* Water absorbs strongly in infrared regions around 1450 nm and 1940 nm.
* Chlorophyll absorbs blue (around 430 nm) and red (around 660 nm).
* Sodium emits at 589 nm.

##### Match with Known Spectral Databases

Unknown sample spectrum is compared against standard libraries:

* Atomic absorption spectra
* Molecular IR spectra
* UV–Visible spectra
* NMR, Raman, X-ray spectra

##### Determine the Chemical Structure or Composition

From the spectral pattern, one can identify:

* Functional groups
* Elements present
* Bond types
* Molecular environment
* Impurities or mixtures
</md></sn><sn><md>### Major Types of Spectroscopy{.text-center}

| **Type of Spectroscopy**                 | **Description / What It Studies**                      | **Useful For / Applications**                                                                                   |
| ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **UV–Visible Spectroscopy**              | Studies electronic transitions.                        | • Detecting conjugated compounds <br> • Measuring concentration <br> • Analyzing pigments and colored compounds |
| **Infrared (IR) Spectroscopy**           | Studies molecular vibrations.                          | • Functional groups (OH, NH, C=O, etc.) <br> • Organic compounds <br> • Soil minerals and clays                 |
| **Raman Spectroscopy**                   | Measures scattering of light.                          | • Studying molecular structure <br> • Mineral composition <br> • Water-free or hydrated samples                 |
| **Atomic Absorption Spectroscopy (AAS)** | Detects metal ions with high precision.                | Used in soil, water, and food testing.                                                                          |
| **Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR)**     | Reveals molecular structure and bonding environment.   | Structural analysis and chemical environment determination.                                                     |
| **X-ray Spectroscopy (XRF, XRD)**        | Used for elemental analysis and crystalline structure. | Identifying elements and crystal structure.                                                                     |</md></sn>